  "enhanced_information": "Pneumonia caused by Pneumocystis carinii (now known as Pneumocystis jirovecii) is primarily seen in immunocompromised patients, particularly those with HIV/AIDS. The standard treatment for this type of pneumonia is Cotrimoxazole (Trimethoprim-Sulfamethoxazole), which is effective against P. jirovecii. Other options such as Penicillin, Kanamycin, and Levofloxacin are not effective for this specific infection. The reasoning chains correctly identify Cotrimoxazole as the first-line treatment, while the other antibiotics are not indicated for P. jirovecii pneumonia. Evidence paths related to Cotrimoxazole's effectiveness support this consensus, while paths discussing Levofloxacin and Kanamycin do not provide relevant support for treating P. jirovecii pneumonia."
